<tr>
<td style="text-align: right; font-size: 115%; padding-top: 0.6em;">
<div class="noprint plainlinks hlist navbar mini" style="">
<ul>
<li class="nv-view"><a href="/wiki/Template:Taxation" title="Template:Taxation"><span title="View this template" style="">v</span></a></li>
<li class="nv-talk"><a href="/wiki/Template_talk:Taxation" title="Template talk:Taxation"><span title="Discuss this template" style="">t</span></a></li>
<li class="nv-edit"><a class="external text" href="//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Taxation&amp;action=edit"><span title="Edit this template" style="">e</span></a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>A <b>capital gains tax</b> (<b>CGT</b>) is a <a href="/wiki/Tax" title="Tax">tax</a> on <a href="/wiki/Capital_gain" title="Capital gain">capital gains</a>, the profit realized on the sale of a non-inventory <a href="/wiki/Asset" title="Asset">asset</a> that was purchased at a lower price. The most common capital gains are realized from the sale of stocks, bonds, precious metals and property. Not all countries implement a capital gains tax and most have different rates of taxation for individuals and corporations.</p>
<p>For <a href="/wiki/Equities" title="Equities" class="mw-redirect">equities</a>, an example of a popular and <a href="/wiki/Liquidity" title="Liquidity" class="mw-redirect">liquid</a> asset, national and state legislation often has a large array of fiscal obligations that must be respected regarding capital gains. Taxes are charged by the state over the transactions, <a href="/wiki/Dividend" title="Dividend">dividends</a> and capital gains on the <a href="/wiki/Stock_market" title="Stock market">stock market</a>. However, these fiscal obligations may vary from jurisdiction to jurisdiction because, among other reasons, it could be assumed that <a href="/wiki/Taxation" title="Taxation" class="mw-redirect">taxation</a> is already incorporated into the <a href="/wiki/Stock_price" title="Stock price" class="mw-redirect">stock price</a> through the different taxes companies pay to the state, or that tax-free stock market operations are useful to boost <a href="/wiki/Economic_growth" title="Economic growth">economic growth</a>.</p>
